Synchronous vs Asynchronous JavaScript

🔹 What is Synchronous Code?

👉 Synchronous = line-by-line execution

Each task waits for the previous one to finish
Nothing moves forward until the current task is done

console.log("Start");
console.log("Middle");
console.log("End");

//Start
Middle
End

👉 Asynchronous = non-blocking execution

Long tasks run in the background
JavaScript does NOT wait
Moves to next line immediately

console.log("Start");

setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Inside Timeout");
}, 2000);

console.log("End");



//output
Start
End
Inside Timeout




💡 Why JavaScript Needs Asynchronous Behavior

JavaScript is single-threaded (one thing at a time).

👉 Without async behavior:

App would freeze while waiting
No user interaction possible
Bad user experience


🧠 Real-Life Analogy

Ordering food 🍔

Synchronous:
You wait at the counter until food is ready (blocked)
Asynchronous:
You order → sit → get food when ready (non-blocking)

🌐 Real Examples of Async Tasks
API calls (fetching data from server)
Timers (setTimeout, setInterval)
File reading
Database queries

API Example
console.log("Start");

fetch("https://api.example.com/data")
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => console.log(data));

console.log("End");

//Output
Start
End
(data comes later)


Blocking vs Non-Blocking
| Feature         | Blocking (Sync) ❌ | Non-Blocking (Async) ✅ |
| --------------- | ----------------- | ---------------------- |
| Execution       | One by one        | Parallel-like          |
| Waiting         | Yes               | No                     |
| Performance     | Poor              | Better                 |
| User Experience | Freezes           | Smooth                 |



🔄 How Async Works (Concept)

👉 JavaScript uses:

Call stack
Web APIs
Callback queue
Call Stack → Web API → Callback Queue → Call Stack


1. setTimeout goes to Web API
2. Timer finishes
3. Callback enters queue
4. Runs when stack is empty



